INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Late. One work lamp. DUTCH alone at the plywood table with the
build drawings, his binder, and a slide rule.

He counts scrubber cartridges on the parts shelf against a line in
the drawing. Counts again. Sits down slow.

He works the slide rule. Writes a figure. Works it again from the
other direction, and writes the same figure, and boxes it, twice.

INSERT — THE PAD: CO2 SCRUBBER CAPACITY: 62 HRS. × 4.

Dutch looks at the boxed line a long time. Then he gets up, crosses
to crate number one — finished, gleaming under the tarp — pulls the
tarp off, undogs the lid, and opens it.

Inside: a molded couch. Head cradle. Restraint webbing. Shaped
exactly like a man.

Dutch stands there looking into it a long time, one hand on the
lid.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - THE NEXT EVENING

All of them: the four olds, Joss, Tito, and MACK, called in. The
build drawing lies on the plywood table with Dutch's pad on top of
it, the boxed figure facing up.

DUTCH:
I ran the consumables. Sixty-two hours of scrubber capacity, times
four units. A crate swap needs a forklift and nerve. A scrub needs
a wrench and a bad day. Nobody — nobody — builds sixty-two hours
of breathing into a decoy.

He turns the drawing around to face Mack.

DUTCH:
It's a life-support system with a museum sticker on it. I should
know. I wrote it. So you tell this room, Boone, and you tell it
plain. Who's riding?

Silence. Joss looks from Dutch to Mack. Tito has stopped moving.

Mack looks around the table, one face at a time, and says it plain.

MACK:
So. You gentlemen want to go to the Moon?

Joss sits down on a sawhorse without checking it's there.

JOSS:
Wait. WAIT.

MACK:
The mission flies July first no matter what anybody in this
building does. Six crates ride up empty to bring six flags down —
unless four of them ride up full. Nobody can stop the taking from
down here. Somebody can be standing there when they come to take.

GUNNY:
And if this room says no?

MACK:
Then six crates fly empty, and I lose track of some scrap, and
we all went to a lot of trouble over a carousel.

Quiet. The stove has no fire in it tonight, and nobody moves to
light one.

Stitch gets up, walks to the open crate, and looks into the couch
a moment. Then he climbs in, lies back, and sets his hat on his
chest.

STITCH:
Snug.

Gunny crosses to the gear shelf and starts counting scrubber
cartridges into ranks of four, marking the shelf edge with a
grease pencil.

GUNNY:
Well. Now what do they take from us — cancel my Medicare on the
Moon?

Dutch squares his pad on the drawing.

DUTCH:
The spec holds. I sized it.

Every face turns to Cricket, last.

Cricket looks at the crate a long moment. Then he walks over to
it, sits down on the edge of it, and starts unlacing his boots.

CRICKET:
Somebody time me getting in. We'll want a number.

TITO:
(quiet, a hand flat on the crate)
Tapped twice. She'll hold.

JOSS:
You're all insane. Every one of you. What do you need from me?

MACK:
The build order changes Monday. Nothing else does.

He takes out the pocket notebook, writes one line, and puts it
away.

CUT TO:
